n class=\"ei\">-ed<\/span> forms and do not add <span class=\"ei\">-s<\/span> to the 3rd person singular form:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">He can speak three languages.<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">She will try and visit tomorrow.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Modal verbs are followed by the infinitive of another verb without <span class=\"eb\">to<\/span>. The exceptions are <span class=\"eb\">ought to<\/span>, <span class=\"eb\">have to<\/span> and <span class=\"eb\">used to<\/span>:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">You must find a job.<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">You ought to stop smoking.<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">I used to smoke but I gave up two years ago.<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Questions are formed without <span class=\"eb\">do<\/span>\/<span class=\"eb\">does<\/span> in the present, or <span class=\"eb\">did<\/span> in the past:<ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"unx\">Can I invite Mary?<\/span><\/li><li><span class=\"unx\">Should I have invited Mary?<\/span><\/li><\/ul><\/li><li class=\"li\">Negative sentences are formed with <span class=\"eb\">not<\/span> or the short form <span class=\"eb\">-n\u2019t<\/span> and do not use <span class=\"eb\">do<\/span>\/<span class=\"eb\">does<\/span> or <span class=\"eb\">did<\/span>.<\/li><\/ul><span class=\"p\">You will find more help with how to use modal verbs at the dictionary entries for each verb.<\/span><\/span><\/div> <\/li><div class=\"idioms\"><h2 class=\"h2\">Idioms<\/h2><div class=\"d1\"><span class=\"idm-g\"><h3 class=\"idioms_h2\">be that as it may<\/h3><li class=\"sense\"><span class=\"sensetop\"><span class=\"labels\">(formal)<\/span><\/span> <span class=\"def\">despite that<\/span> <ul class=\"eg\"><li><span class=\"x\">I know that he has tried hard; be that as it may, his work is just not good enough.<\/span><\/li><\/ul>  <\/li><\/span><span class=\"idm-g\"><h3 class=\"idioms_h2\">may\/might (just) as well do something<\/h3><li